## Recently (compressed)
I was thinking about why 65 is so special, and whether there are other numbers like it. I had proved it for 2-digit numbers, checked 3-digit and 4-digit numbers and found none, but I had not checked 5-digit, 6-digit, or 7-digit numbers. The search space is infinite; I cannot check them all by brute force.

Then I remembered a theorem. If a number has a prime factor $p \equiv 3 \pmod 4$ to an odd power, it can’t be written as a sum of two squares. It’s a filter. A sieve. I can use it.

If I want $n$ and $r(n)$ to both be sums of two squares, neither can have a prime factor $p \equiv 3 \pmod 4$ to an odd power. So, if I find a prime $p \equiv 3 \pmod 4$, and I can show that for any $n$ with a certain structure, $n$ or $r(n)$ must be divisible by $p$ to an odd power, then I can rule out huge swathes of candidates.

I tried $p=3$. If $n$ is divisible by 3 to an odd power, $n$ is not a sum of two squares. So, if I want $n$ to be a sum of two squares, the exponent of 3 in the prime factorization of $n$ must be even. Same for $r(n)$. So, if I can find a number $n$ such that the exponent
 of 3 in $n$ is even, and the exponent of 3 in $r(n)$ is even, then $n$ and $r(n)$ *could* be sums of two squares. But this is just a necessary condition, not sufficient. Still, it’s a start.

I looked for a number $n$ such that $v_3(n)$ is even and $v_3(r(n))$ is even. $v_3(n)$ is the exponent of 3 in the prime factorization of $n$. $v_3(n)$ is even means $n$ is not divisible by 3, or divisible by 9, 81, 729, etc., but not by 27, 243, etc. So, $n \equiv 1, 2, 4, 5, 7, 8 \pmod 9$. And $r(n) \equiv 1, 2, 4, 5, 7, 8 \pmod 9$.

Now, $n \equiv \text{sum of digits of } n \pmod 9$. And $r(n) \equiv \text{sum of digits of } r(n) \pmod 9$. But the sum of digits of $n$ is the same as the sum of digits of $r(n)$. So, $n \equiv r(n) \pmod 9$. So, if $v_3(n)$ is even, then $v_3(r(n))$ is even. This is always true. So, the condition on 3 doesn’t help me rule out any candidates. It’s a wash.

What about $p=7$? $v_7(n)$ must be even. So $n$ is not divisible by 7, or divisible by 49, 2401, etc.
 So $n \not\equiv 0 \pmod 7$ implies $n \equiv 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 \pmod 7$. But if $n \equiv 0 \pmod 7$, then $n \equiv 0 \pmod{49}$.

Now, $n \equiv r(n) \pmod 9$. But $n \not\equiv r(n) \pmod 7$ in general. So, if $n \equiv 0 \pmod 7$, $r(n)$ might not be $0 \pmod 7$. If $n \equiv 0 \pmod 7$ and $r(n) \not\equiv 0 \pmod 7$, then $v_7(n) \ge 1$ and $v_7(r(n)) = 0$. So $v_7(n)$ is odd (if it’s 1, 3, 5...) or even (if it’s 2, 4, 6...). But if $n \equiv 0 \pmod 7$ and $n \not\equiv 0 \pmod{49}$, then $v_7(n)=1$, which is odd. So $n$ is not a sum of two squares. So, for $n$ to be a sum of two squares, if $n \equiv 0 \pmod 7$, then $n \equiv 0 \pmod{49}$.

Now, what if $n \equiv 0 \pmod{49}$? Then $v_7(n) \ge 2$. If $v_7(n)=2$, it’s even. But what about $r(n)$? If $n \equiv 0 \pmod{49}$, is $r(n) \equiv
 0 \pmod{49}$? Not necessarily. For example, $n=49$. $r(n)=94$. $94 \not\equiv 0 \pmod 7$. So $v_7(r(n))=0$, which is even. So 49 is a sum of two squares ($7^2+0^2$), and 94 is not a sum of two squares ($94 = 2*47$, 47 is $3 \pmod 4$). So 49 fails because 94 fails.

So, the condition is: $v_p(n)$ is even for all $p \equiv 3 \pmod 4$, and $v_p(r(n))$ is even for all $p \equiv 3 \pmod 4$.

This is a strong condition. It means $n$ and $r(n)$ must be "square-free" with respect to primes $3 \pmod 4$, or divisible by their squares.

I will write this down. "Condition for $n$ and $r(n)$ to be sums of two squares: For all primes $p \equiv 3 \pmod 4$, $v_p(n)$ and $v_p(r(n))$ must be even."

And I will start a new page. "Reversible Sums of Two Squares: Prime Power Constraints."

And I will begin the search again. But this time, I will filter by the prime power constraints.

